text:
Taylor Swift’s brand-new single, “Look What You Made Me Do,” seems obviously about her feuds with people like Kanye West, Kim Kardashian, Calvin Harris, and Katy Perry. But what if they were actually all about a fictional character instead? A corner of the Internet is convinced the lyrics actually tell the story of Arya Stark from Game of Thrones, and the idea makes a lot of sense, if you think about it.

This content is imported from Giphy. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.

Both Mashable and Entertainment Weekly broke down just how similar the lyrics are to Arya’s character on the HBO show. And they really do reflect Arya’s transformation from a little kid into a badass assassin with a list of grudges.

Just a few examples: “I don’t like your tilted stage/The role you made me play/Of the fool” could be a reference to the actors in Braavos who put on a version of the Stark family’s life—and painted her father, Ned Stark as a buffoon. “I don’t like your kingdom keys/They once belonged to me” could be a reference to Cersei Lannister, who rules the Seven Kingdoms after her family’s treachery killed Ned, who was the hand of the king. "You ask me for a place to sleep / Locked me out and threw a feast" could be a reference to Walder Frey, who locked members of her family in his home for the Red Wedding massacre, while she was locked out. And of course, “I’ve got a list of names and yours is in red, underlined/I check it once, then I check it twice” could be a direct reference to Arya’s list of people she intends to kill.

This content is imported from Giphy. You may be able to find the same content in another format, or you may be able to find more information, at their web site.

Clearly, Twitter took notice of this pretty quickly, and either lived for the comparison or rolled their eyes at the idea that a pop star like Taylor could be as ruthless as Arya. But who knows: Maybe Taylor is a huge Game of Thrones fan and sees herself in the girl who was wronged—and who now wants to take down all her enemies.
